Haven't watched the entire video yet but want to comment. Initially, I used to consider Ajay as just a routine college vlogger who used to review colleges, review gadgets, compare colleges and make a podcast about colleges. 

But then your "Still Unplaced" video was out and I was proven wrong about you here because not only it was spectacular but also it has been transitioned from standard vlogging-editing to great storytelling- magnificent cinematography- sharp editing which can make any emotionless person hooked and booked. And I think that's the turning point of your journey. Later on, more and more quality videos were made ex- "Finally Placed", "The Last Semester" "Last Day of Engineering" etc. 

BOOM, one day I get notifications about your trip to HEAVEN. I watched it, and I must say that the video kept me intrigued till the end; here you proved why you are one of the great vloggers in the budding YT community. 

When I met you during the process of this video, I saw that zeal in your eyes (P.S. I have already seen that in videos only, but then I saw that in person). With the enthusiasm you were showing some of the rushes that you shot, let me tell you, you were showing all of them literally like an overexcited baby🤭. You were talking about Irafan Junejo Sir and how he has motivated you for this shot and many more. I hope one day he will see your work and be proud of his obedient student🏆.

At last, Let me tell you, I have witnessed your growth immensely. We have crap vloggers having subscribers millions but their existence is the biggest question mark in vlogging industry? But then we have a hidden gem like you who always thinks out of the box and does par excellence. 

From "TECH SKOOL" to "Ajay Raj - The Filmmaker", You have come a long way. Now when you look back, I'm sure that you, your parents, your brother, your friends, and your subscribers will be proud to see Today's Ajay😇. 

Lastly, wishing you nothing but just exponential growth📈. Deeply- rooting for your upcoming film-making journey.  📷

The guy is absolutely right, alcohol is the last thing on a trip to Ladakh, especially at a place like Pangong. Alcohol only gives you temporary warmth while reducing the oxygen in the body. A simple explanation from internet search: "Alcohol widens your blood vessels, making more blood flow to your skin. That makes you blush and feel warm and toasty. But not for long. The heat from that extra blood passes right out of your body, causing your temperature to drop." People really need to learn to enjoy a place without involving alcohol. I have heard so many stories of people taken to hospital and even dying just because they felt alcohol will give them the "warmth and fun". This needs to stop.

It's my request to all traveling from a low altitude area to please avoid alcohol when you're visiting a high altitude area for a week or 2. One thing people might forget on a Ladakh trip is the altitude gain when visiting places like Pangong, Tso Moriri, Hanle etc. One gets acclimatized in Leh which is at 11.5k feet. However, Pangong is at 13.8k feet. For every 2000 feet gain in altitude above 8000 feet, the body needs to acclimatize. So when you're going from Leh to Pangong, you are no longer acclimatized.

Note: Khardung La is at an altitude of 17582 feet. The board there mentions otherwise and they have not updated it for obvious reasons. In comparison, Chang La and Kaksang La are higher.

Hi Ajay,
I am your alumni from mech + auto (2k13 Batch).

First, congratulation on the placement. 
some key pointers for you.

1. Don't let be the only achievement in your life that you graduated from DTU.
2. Keep yourself motivated and keep on learning new things (it may be any skill). 
3. Being from the mech side and working as a developer, taking myself and some of my friends into consideration, I can say only one thing to you. the sky is the only limit for you.

having said those things. I would suggest you to prepare a guide (if you want) for upcoming graduates where you explain how to maintain a study/social life in college. ( even if a single person follows it, it will be worth it).
I know this is not a big thing, but most of the students live in this delusion ("TCS/Infosys me to lag hi jayegi")
It is not that easy and once you graduate from college life becomes exponentially hard and getting a job/going into a new field becomes whole another level of pain.


If you would, let the fuchha's know. learning new skills is as important as getting good grades. (be it solid works/AUTOCAD for mech or A new language for CS/ or learning the very basics (Data Structures).

again, Congrats and best of luck in your future endeavors!

My comment is going to be ignored but if you are reading...Then read it once...

So I am also happy for Ajay bhai..He has great editing skills ..Hats off to him...

But he never did coding...He started coding rigorously 2 or 2.5 month back and now he is placed in Product based company which tier 3 student dies for...

But see...this is difference...People brag about ..you r from tier3 ..so u can also get chances...You must do this, do that...crack gsoc...become 5 star...

But this guy literally never did DP of enough level...And started from basic recursion...
He also was not comfortable in binary Top View question...

But guess what... Everything works out because he got 30+ chances....and still if not placed..

But for off campus ...Its so hard...
I was just able to crack Infosys....And mind it... Infosys was not easy....

But hell yeah...
I dont have any issues...I am happy for him...

But people like Nishant chahar, Ajay Raj,etc are not educators. 
(Atleast they are not teaching on YouTube for free)

Follow Anuj Bhaiya/Pepcoding/Striver/adityaverma  more....Just see their videos Youtube views on coding questions..
And compare them with any road map video.

*We all are interested in knowing and not doing.*

If any tier3 friend like me is here...then please understand.... Start working...Do Practice..... Understand concepts, 
do development...
I am not saying you have to be super smart..

But cracking good 6+lpa job is also good thing ..

We won't get chance..20 or 30+ product based company won't visit our campus....

So please do work...


And you must also consider luck...Because in interview you might get repeated question. You migh already have seen in gfg or Glassdoor before 5 min of interview.


But nowadays cracking first round of online assessment is also tough....

Atlast Nothing...I myself cracked 10lpa job....I am happy with that...
I have applied at various companies...But no response...

That's why tier matters...So don't believe tier of college doesn't matter...


Work like hell yeahhh 🎉🎉🎉

PS : No offence for Nishant, Ajay kr love babbar...They are good at their place...But I hate fact that they are earning frok our fear. I might be wrong..but thats what my view is....

Its their fate...and this is our fate

मेने अपना सफर मनाली से शुरू किया था,  में अकेला था । चंडीगढ़ से n 250 रेंट पर लेकर गया था में। मेने अपना रास्ता खुद ने चुना था और मेरे सफर का पहला पड़ाव जो था वो शिमला था फिर पूह गांव , फिर टाबो,काजा,कॉमिक, हिक्किम, लांगजा,और फिर स्पीति घाटी का आखिरी गांव लोसार था । चंद्रताल नहीं जा सका ।   मुझे याद है , जब में घाटी की शुरआत में एक सेना की एक चौकी आती है( वहा से टाबो या स्पीति घाटीका रास्ता शुरू होता है ) वहा से जब में निकल रहा था तो क्योंकि रुक नहीं सकते आप( उस वक्त एक हेलीकॉप्टर भी उड़ान भरने वाला था) मेरे आसू गिर रहे थे और मेरी चेहरे की मुसकुराहट रुक ही नही रही थी और में जाए जा रहा था कर्रीब 12 - 13  मिनट तक  ऐसा ही चलता रहा ।
 काजा से थोड़ा पहले हवाईअड्डा (Helipad) पर  रात को 2बजे अकेला था रात को जब मेने आसमान  की तरफ देखा तो तब भी यही हुआ मेरे साथ ।

मुझे 22 दिसम्बर को 3 महीने हो जायेंगे स्पीति से वापिस आकर 

लेकिन में जब भी फोटो देखता हु वहा के तो आज भी मेरे साथ यही होता है ,अंदर से इतनी खुशी होती है की बता नहीं सकता और आंखे थोड़ी थोड़ी भीगी भीगी सी हो जाती है ।

How to make plans for long term goals ( focussing on JEE )..

Break goals into numerically or any scalable figure, so you can keep track of progress. Starting with a 2 year jee program ( to score 360 marks in 2 years )

Let's assume 

Start date : April 2020

End date : Mar 2022 ( 24 months )

If you keep 4 months as backup ( for revision, breaks and possible vacations ) - months Left : 20Months.

Therefore, goal must be to increase 360/20 = 18 ( approx 5 questions ) per week.

Therefore your goal should be to increase your JEE score by 18marks or do 5 extra questions per months for 10 months. ( These questions need to be done at pressured environments - look for mock Jee mains happening at different coaching centres )

This is the best startegy to create history after Kalpit Veerwal. All you need is patience, consistency and hardwork.

Precison and Timing.

Same for droppers, select a number supossedly 360 ( if you have enough believe and think you can study 14hrs per day ), else fix a smaller target like 250. Idea is the target should be scalable.

So, for drop year ( to top Jee ), we have around 10 months ( 2 months buffer - revision, practice, vacations, relationships etc. )

We need around 360/10 ( or 36 marks or 9 questions ) to increase per month. This again is very tough. And here there is not only consistency, hardwork, and other stuff.

Passion would be needed.

Since consitency and hardwork is a muscle. And every muscle to perform at its best, needs drive, needs fuel. Passion is the fuel.
